A Cumulative-Stiffness Description of Galactic Rotation Curves
=============================================================

Author: Martin Ollett
Year: 2026


------------------------------------------------------------
ABSTRACT
------------------------------------------------------------

We investigate a cumulative-stiffness description of galactic
rotation curves in which the gravitational response is governed not
primarily by Euclidean radius, but by an accumulated stiffness
coordinate

    u(r) = ∫_0^r m(s) ds.

The normalized rotational velocity is taken to follow exponential
saturation in a cumulative response field S(r),

    V(r)/V_inf = 1 − exp[−S(r)].

The central empirical result of the SPARC tests is that when the
response is expressed in the cumulative stiffness coordinate u, the
field becomes nearly linear:

    S(u) ≈ C + A u,

with median linear-fit goodness

    R^2 ≈ 0.999

across the working sample. Equivalently,

    dS/du ≈ const.

This implies that the weighted radial operators and nonlocal kernel
reconstructions explored earlier are best interpreted as effective
r-space representations of a simpler underlying accumulation law in
source coordinate.

Normalizing by the turnover-scale stiffness budget u(R_s) yields the
zero-free-parameter response law

    S(r) = u(r) / u(R_s),

and therefore

    V(r)/V_inf = 1 − exp[−u(r)/u(R_s)].

When tested directly against the validated pooled galaxy master curve,
this parameter-free model gives pooled stretched-exponential fit
parameters

    ν ≈ 0.961,
    x_0 ≈ 0.979,

close to the empirical target values

    ν ≈ 0.953,
    x_0 ≈ 1.003.

Two source constructions were explored for the local loading field.
The first uses baryonic loading alone,

    m_b(r) = ( g_b(r) / g_* )^γ,
    g_b(r) = V_b(r)^2 / r,

with empirically preferred exponent

    γ ≈ 0.34.

The second uses a symmetric hybrid loading law,

    m(r) ∝ [ g_b(r) g_obs(r) ]^(1/3),

which also reproduces the observed master-curve structure and yields
forward radial-acceleration slopes close to those measured directly in
the working sample. In this sense, the observed galaxy master curve is
consistent with linear accumulation in cumulative stiffness coordinate
followed by exponential saturation, while the remaining theoretical
question concerns the origin of the local loading law itself.



------------------------------------------------------------
1. INTRODUCTION
------------------------------------------------------------

Galaxy rotation curves exhibit a characteristic universal structure
when scaled by asymptotic velocity V_inf and turnover radius R_s.
Empirically, normalized rotation curves collapse onto a stretched-
exponential master curve

    V(r)/V_inf = 1 − exp[−(r/(R_s x_0))^ν].

The origin of this functional form is usually treated as empirical.

In this work we show that the same structure emerges naturally from a
cumulative-stiffness description in which the relevant coordinate is
not radius alone, but an accumulated loading budget

    u(r) = ∫_0^r m(s) ds.

Within this framework the galaxy response field S is found to be
approximately linear in u, and the observed rotation-curve master
curve follows from exponential saturation of that accumulated
response.

The main empirical claim of the paper is therefore not a new fitted
radial formula, but a reduction of the problem:

    the observed stretched-exponential curve in r-space is the
    projection of a simpler near-linear accumulation law in
    cumulative stiffness coordinate.

Earlier weighted operators and kernel interpretations are retained as
useful effective descriptions, but are no longer treated as
fundamental once the source coordinate u is used.



------------------------------------------------------------
2. THEORY
------------------------------------------------------------

2.1 Cumulative response framework

We introduce a cumulative stiffness coordinate

    u(r) = ∫_0^r m(s) ds,

where m(r) is the local loading or response-density field. The
normalized cumulative response field is written

    S(r) = u(r) / u(R_s),

and the observable velocity response is assumed to saturate
exponentially:

    V(r)/V_inf = 1 − exp[−S(r)].

Thus the complete dynamical content of the model is carried by the
loading field m(r), while the mapping from radius to observable
velocity is fixed by cumulative normalization and exponential
saturation.


2.2 Baryonic loading form

The first local source law considered is baryonic loading,

    m_b(r) = ( g_b(r) / g_* )^γ,

where

    g_b(r) = V_b(r)^2 / r

is the baryonic acceleration profile, g_* is a reference acceleration,
and γ is a loading exponent.

This gives the cumulative baryonic stiffness coordinate

    u_b(r) = ∫_0^r ( g_b(s) / g_* )^γ ds.

When this construction is used, the SPARC tests identify a preferred
effective exponent

    γ ≈ 0.34.


2.3 Source-coordinate reduction

The decisive empirical reduction found in the SPARC tests is that the
response field becomes nearly linear when written in cumulative source
coordinate:

    S(u) ≈ C + A u.

Equivalently,

    dS/du ≈ const.

This means that the more complicated weighted operators and kernel
descriptions explored earlier are not fundamental. They are effective
descriptions of a simpler law written in the wrong variable.

Using the turnover-scale stiffness budget u(R_s) for normalization
gives the natural zero-free-parameter law

    S(r) = u(r) / u(R_s),

hence

    V(r)/V_inf = 1 − exp[−u(r)/u(R_s)].


2.4 Relation to the stretched-exponential master curve

Since u(r) is generally a nonlinear function of radius, a simple
exponential in S(u) becomes a stretched exponential in r over the
observed galaxy window:

    V(r)/V_inf = 1 − exp[−(r/(R_s x_0))^ν].

Thus the observed master-curve parameters (x_0, ν) arise as the
r-space projection of a simpler linear accumulation law in cumulative
stiffness coordinate.


2.5 Differential form

The normalized response law

    S(r) = u(r) / u(R_s)

implies

    dS/dr = m(r) / u(R_s).

Thus the response gradient at each radius is set by the local loading
field, while the overall normalization is set by the total stiffness
budget accumulated up to the turnover radius.


2.6 Hybrid cube-root loading law

A later extension replaces purely baryonic loading by a symmetric
hybrid law involving both baryonic and realized accelerations:

    m(r) ∝ [ g_b(r) g_obs(r) ]^(1/3),

where

    g_obs(r) = V_obs(r)^2 / r.

This form is motivated empirically by the later SPARC tests and
structurally by the requirement of marginal cumulative transport in
the outer galaxy. Under the outer asymptotics

    g_b(r) ~ G M_b / r^2,
    g_obs(r) ~ V_inf^2 / r,

the product scales as

    g_b g_obs ~ r^(-3),

so the cube-root law gives

    m(r) ~ r^(-1),

hence

    u(r) ~ ln r.

This logarithmic accumulation is the marginal case between divergent
outer accumulation and overly localized inner accumulation, making the
cube-root law the natural symmetric scale-free transport law in this
class of cumulative response systems.

The hybrid law does not replace the u-space reduction; rather, it
provides a candidate local loading field for the same cumulative
response framework.



------------------------------------------------------------
3. EARLIER EFFECTIVE DESCRIPTIONS
------------------------------------------------------------

Before the u-space reduction was identified, several effective
r-space descriptions were explored.

3.1 Unweighted candidate stiffness profiles

The initial tests considered cumulative laws of the form

    S(r) = ∫_0^r m(s) ds

using several candidate profile families:

    1. power-law stiffness
    2. exponential-core stiffness
    3. density-coupled stiffness

These produced effective master-curve exponents close to the observed
value ν ≈ 0.94 across the SPARC working range.


3.2 Weighted cumulative operator

A later empirical fit introduced an effective weighted cumulative law

    S(r) = ∫_0^r s^κ m(s) ds

with baryonic loading exponent

    γ ≈ 0.34

and effective radial weighting exponent

    κ ≈ −0.2.

This operator reproduced both the pooled master curve and a strong
two-variable horizon relation across the working sample.


3.3 Reinterpretation of the weighted operator

Subsequent tests showed that neither a universal nonlocal kernel nor a
fundamental weighted radial measure is required once the response is
written in cumulative stiffness coordinate u.

The weighted operator is therefore best interpreted as an effective
r-space approximation to the simpler source-coordinate law

    dS/du ≈ const.



------------------------------------------------------------
4. DATA
------------------------------------------------------------

The analysis uses the SPARC galaxy database containing high-quality
rotation curves and baryonic mass models.

For each galaxy we use

    • measured radii
    • baryonic velocity components
    • observed rotation curves
    • fitted turnover radius R_s.

Galaxies with insufficient sampling were excluded, leaving

    N = 70 galaxies

in the working sample used for the cumulative-stiffness tests.



------------------------------------------------------------
5. EMPIRICAL TESTS
------------------------------------------------------------

The Colab analysis proceeded in several stages.

5.1 Baseline cumulative-stiffness tests

Several unweighted stiffness families were tested to determine whether
they reproduce the observed pooled master-curve exponent.

5.2 Baryonic loading tests

The local baryonic loading law

    m_b(r) = ( g_b(r) / g_* )^γ

was inferred empirically, yielding

    γ ≈ 0.34.

5.3 Effective weighted-operator tests

An effective weighted cumulative operator of the form

    S(r) = ∫_0^r s^κ m_b(s) ds

was tested and found to reproduce the pooled master curve and weighted
horizon law with κ near −0.2.

5.4 Kernel and metric-closure tests

Kernel reconstructions, smoothed anchor models, and self-consistent
metric closures were explored as possible first-principles origins of
the weighted operator. These descriptions proved useful as effective
intermediate models but did not isolate a universal underlying kernel
or exact metric law.

5.5 Source-coordinate reduction

The decisive later tests introduced the cumulative stiffness
coordinate

    u(r) = ∫_0^r m(s) ds

and examined the reconstructed response S(u).

These tests showed:

    1. S(u) is nearly linear galaxy by galaxy
    2. dS/du is nearly constant
    3. the parameter-free normalization S = u/u(R_s) reproduces the
       validated pooled master curve to good accuracy

for the baryonic-loading construction.

5.6 Hybrid loading tests

The local source law was then generalized to the symmetric hybrid form

    m(r) ∝ [ g_b(r) g_obs(r) ]^(1/3),

and tested against both the pooled master curve and the radial-
acceleration relation. These tests showed that the same cumulative
framework continues to reproduce the observed rotation-curve collapse,
while the forward-predicted RAR slopes closely match those measured
directly from the working sample.



------------------------------------------------------------
6. RESULTS
------------------------------------------------------------

6.1 Baseline unweighted candidate-profile tests

The initial cumulative-stiffness families produced the corrected
effective exponents

    Model                               Median ν
    ------------------------------------------------
    power-law stiffness                  0.940
    density-coupled stiffness            0.947
    exponential-core stiffness           0.950

showing that cumulative loading can naturally generate the observed
stretched-exponential behaviour.


6.2 Baryonic loading field

The later SPARC tests identified the empirical baryonic loading law

    m_b(r) = ( g_b(r) / g_* )^γ

with best-fit value

    γ ≈ 0.34.


6.3 Linear response in cumulative stiffness coordinate

The central first-principles result is that the reconstructed response
field becomes nearly linear in cumulative stiffness coordinate:

    S(u) ≈ C + A u.

Across the working sample the linear fit gives

    median linear R^2   ≈ 0.9993
    mean linear R^2     ≈ 0.9957

while the derivative test gives

    trimmed median CV(dS/du) ≈ 0.053.

Thus the response density in u-space is nearly constant:

    dS/du ≈ const.


6.4 Failure of nontrivial power-law response in u

The same tests show that a nontrivial power-law response

    S(u) ∝ u^α

is not preferred. The fitted exponents are very small,

    trimmed median α ≈ 0.029,

and the power-law fits are poor compared with the linear model.

This indicates that the natural first-principles structure is not a
power law in u, but linear accumulation.


6.5 Zero-free-parameter response law

Normalizing the response by the turnover-scale stiffness budget gives

    S(r) = u(r) / u(R_s),

hence

    V(r)/V_inf = 1 − exp[−u(r)/u(R_s)].

For the baryonic-loading construction, direct comparison against the
validated pooled master curve gives

    median RMSE         ≈ 0.044
    mean RMSE           ≈ 0.053

across the working sample.

Fitting a stretched-exponential master curve to the model prediction
gives

    pooled ν_pred       ≈ 0.961
    pooled x_0_pred     ≈ 0.979

close to the empirical reference values

    ν_ref               ≈ 0.953
    x_0_ref             ≈ 1.003.


6.6 Hybrid cube-root loading

The best symmetric hybrid loading family was found to be close to

    m(r) ∝ [ g_b(r) g_obs(r) ]^(1/3).

For the exact cube-root law, the cumulative response model gives

    median galaxy RMSE to target   ≈ 0.054
    pooled RMSE to target          ≈ 0.063
    pooled ν                       ≈ 1.080
    pooled x_0                     ≈ 0.985.

Thus the cube-root law reproduces the validated master-curve shape at
comparable accuracy while using a structurally distinguished exponent.


6.7 Forward RAR test

Using the exact cube-root loading law in the cumulative response
model and forward-computing the implied observed acceleration gives

    global slope (predicted)       ≈ 0.666
    global slope (observed)        ≈ 0.656

and in the low-acceleration subset

    low-g_b slope (predicted)      ≈ 0.399
    low-g_b slope (observed)       ≈ 0.409

with

    log RMSE(predicted vs observed) ≈ 0.171.

Thus the same cumulative cube-root loading law that reproduces the
rotation-curve master-curve structure also generates radial-
acceleration slopes close to those measured directly from the data.


6.8 Reinterpretation of earlier weighted descriptions

The earlier effective weighted operator with κ ≈ −0.2 reproduced the
data well, but subsequent kernel and coordinate tests showed that it
is not a universal underlying kernel law.

Instead, the weighted radial description is best interpreted as an
effective r-space representation of the simpler first-principles law

    S(r) = u(r) / u(R_s),

with the remaining open issue shifted to the origin of the loading
field m(r) itself.



------------------------------------------------------------
7. DISCUSSION
------------------------------------------------------------

7.1 What is fundamental

The tests support the following hierarchy:

    local loading:
        m(r)

    source coordinate:
        u(r) = ∫_0^r m(s) ds

    linear response:
        dS/du ≈ const

    normalized field:
        S(r) = u(r) / u(R_s)

    velocity response:
        V(r)/V_inf = 1 − exp[−S(r)].

This is the most compact first-principles form isolated by the SPARC
tests.

For a baryonic-only construction one may take

    m(r) = ( g_b(r) / g_* )^γ,
    γ ≈ 0.34.

For a symmetric source-response construction one may instead take

    m(r) ∝ [ g_b(r) g_obs(r) ]^(1/3).


7.2 What is effective

The weighted radial operator

    S(r) = ∫_0^r s^κ m(s) ds

and the associated metric-closure constructions are not required as
fundamental laws once the cumulative source coordinate u is used.

They remain useful as effective summaries in Euclidean radius, but the
tests indicate that the simpler linear u-space law is the underlying
structure.


7.3 Physical interpretation

The preferred interpretation is not that baryons create the entire
gravitational response field from nothing. Rather, local fields load a
response channel whose natural accumulation variable is cumulative
stiffness budget u.

In this picture the observed radial master curve appears because the
mapping from Euclidean radius r to source coordinate u is nonlinear,
while the response in u itself is simple.

The baryonic-only loading law gives an effective empirical
description. The hybrid cube-root law is of special structural
interest because it is the unique symmetric homogeneous local power
law that yields marginal outer transport:

    g_b g_obs ~ r^(-3)    =>    [g_b g_obs]^(1/3) ~ r^(-1),

hence

    u(r) ~ ln r.

This logarithmic growth is the scale-free boundary between divergent
outer accumulation and overly localized inner accumulation.


7.4 Remaining open problem

The present work isolates the first-principles galaxy-scale
reduction, but does not yet derive uniquely which local loading law
must hold in a deeper field theory.

The sharply defined remaining questions are therefore:

    1. why does the response accumulate linearly in cumulative
       stiffness coordinate u?

    2. what deeper field principle selects the local loading law?

    3. is the baryonic-loading exponent γ ≈ 0.34 fundamental, or is
       it an effective approximation to the symmetric cube-root law

           m(r) ∝ [ g_b(r) g_obs(r) ]^(1/3) ?



------------------------------------------------------------
8. TESTABLE PREDICTIONS
------------------------------------------------------------

The source-coordinate formulation makes several direct predictions.

1. rotation curves should be organized primarily by the normalized
   cumulative stiffness budget

       u(r) / u(R_s)

   rather than by radius alone

2. galaxies with different baryonic profiles but similar normalized
   u(r) structure should collapse onto the same response curve

3. deviations from the universal master curve should correspond to
   deviations from linearity in S(u)

4. apparent weighted radial operators inferred in r-space should vary
   across samples, because they are effective Jacobian descriptions of
   the transformation r → u, not universal kernel laws

5. if the hybrid cube-root loading law is correct, then the same
   cumulative framework should reproduce both the rotation-curve
   master curve and the observed RAR slopes from a single transport
   construction

6. any deeper relativistic completion of the framework should recover
   approximately constant response density in source coordinate,

       dS/du ≈ const.



------------------------------------------------------------
9. CONCLUSION
------------------------------------------------------------

A cumulative-stiffness description of gravity naturally generates the
empirical master curve of galactic rotation curves, but the decisive
simplification is obtained only after passing from Euclidean radius to
cumulative stiffness coordinate.

Defining

    u(r) = ∫_0^r m(s) ds

the SPARC working sample shows that the reconstructed response field is
nearly linear in u:

    S(u) ≈ C + A u

or equivalently

    dS/du ≈ const.

Normalizing by the turnover-scale stiffness budget yields the
zero-free-parameter law

    S(r) = u(r) / u(R_s)

and hence

    V(r)/V_inf = 1 − exp[−u(r)/u(R_s)].

For the baryonic-loading construction this reproduces the validated
pooled master-curve behaviour with good accuracy:

    ν_pred ≈ 0.961,
    x_0_pred ≈ 0.979,

close to the empirical target values

    ν ≈ 0.953,
    x_0 ≈ 1.003.

A later symmetric extension shows that the cube-root loading law

    m(r) ∝ [ g_b(r) g_obs(r) ]^(1/3)

also reproduces the master-curve structure and yields forward RAR
slopes close to those measured directly from the sample. This makes
the cube-root law a plausible candidate local transport law within the
same cumulative response framework.

The central conclusion is therefore that the galaxy master curve is
consistent with linear accumulation in cumulative stiffness coordinate
followed by exponential saturation. Earlier weighted radial operators
are best interpreted as effective r-space approximations to this
simpler underlying source-coordinate law, while the remaining open
problem is the origin of the local loading field itself.



